 Atavism: Toward a Neo-Secular View of Religion -- tSecularism, the Christian Ambivalence Toward the Jews, and the Notion of Exile -- t‘‘Eleven Calendars’’: Beyond Secular Time -- tNotes -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor much of the twentieth century, most religious and secular Jewish thinkers believed that they were witnessing a steady, ongoing movement toward secularization. Toward the end of the century, however, as scholars and pundits began to speak of the global resurgence of religion, the normalization of secularism could no longer be considered inevitable. Recent decades have seen the strengthening of Orthodox movements in the United States and in Israel; religious Zionism has grown and radically changed since the 1960s, and new and vibrant nondenominational Jewish movements have emerged.Secularism in Question examines the ways these contemporary revivals of religion prompt a reconsideration of many issues concerning Jews and Judaism from the early modern era to the present. Bringing together scholars of history, religion, philosophy, and literature, this volume illustrates how the categories of "religious" and "secular" have frequently proven far more permeable than fixed. The contributors challenge the problematic assumptions about the development of secularism that emerge from Protestant European and American perspectives and demonstrate that global Jewish experiences necessitate a reappraisal of conventional narratives of secularism. Ultimately, Secularism in Question calls for rethinking the very terms that animate many of the most contentious debates in contemporary Jewish life and far beyond.Contributors: Michal Ben-Horin, Aryeh Edrei, Jonathan Mark Gribetz, Ari Joskowicz, Ethan B. Katz, Eva Lezzi, Vivian Liska, Rachel Manekin, David Myers, Amnon Raz-Krakotzkin, Andrea Schatz, Christophe Schulte, Daniel B. Schwartz, Galili Shahar, Scott Ury.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Jewish Studies.2bisacsh  aJewish Studies.  aReligion.  aWH.1 aBen-Horin, Michal, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEdrei, Arye, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGribetz, Jonathan Marc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJoskowicz, Ari, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJoskowicz, Ari, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKatz, Ethan B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKatz, Ethan B., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLezzi, Eva, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLiska, Vivian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aManekin, Rachel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMyers, David N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRaz-Krakotzkin, Amnon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchatz, Andrea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchulte, Christoph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchwartz, Daniel B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aShahar, Galili, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aUry, Scott, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2015z9783110439687oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theology, Relig. Studies, Jewish Studies 2015z9783110438727oZDB-23-DGF08iTitle is part of eBook package